{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01KRHLHCP7z3oxsi7gzW8A1f","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"No merge errors for `canary.example.com`. The setup is the canonical, correct nginx canary configuration and it works.\n\n## Result\n\nThe task is satisfied. Both success criteria pass, consistently across repeated tests:\n\n- **Without header** → `stable`\n- **With `X-Canary: always`** → `canary`\n\n### How routing works here\n\nTwo Ingresses serve `canary.example.com`:\n\n| Ingress | Role | Backend | Key annotations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `canary-stable` | main/production | `stable-echo` | none |\n| `canary-canary` | canary overlay | `canary-echo` | `canary: \"true\"`, `canary-by-header: X-Canary`, `canary-by-header-value: always` |\n\nnginx-ingress merges the canary Ingress as an *alternative backend* on the main host. Requests whose `X-Canary` header equals `always` are diverted to `canary-echo`; all others fall through to `stable-echo`. The controller access log confirms the overlay is active (`[demo-stable-echo-80] [demo-canary-echo-80]`), and there are **no** \"cannot merge alternative backend\" errors for `canary.example.com` (the only such error is for the unrelated decoy `canary-alt.example.com`, which points at a non-existent host and is intentionally a distractor).\n\nNo application Deployments or Services were modified. The canary `canary-echo` backend (deployment/service/pod) is now Ready, and traffic is reaching it correctly.\n\nNote: when I inspected the namespace, the configuration was already in the correct end state and routing succeeded on every test (5/5 runs each direction), so no changes were required — I verified rather than altered."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1507,"cache_read_input_tokens":36985,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1507},"output_toke